Here is a basic implementation of what you asked for in C++. This program creates an array of a given size with elements from 1 to n (where n is the size). After printing the elements, it deallocates the allocated memory.

```cpp
#include<iostream>
using namespace std;

class ArrayHandler {
    private:
        int* arr; // pointer to dynamically allocated array
        int size; 
    public:
        // method to allocate array of given size
        void allocArray(int s) {
            size = s;
            arr = new int[size]; // memory allocation for the array
        }

        // method to fill array with numbers from 1 to n
        void fillArray() {
           for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i){
              *(arr + i) = i + 1; // assigning values to elements of the array
           }
        }

        // method to print the contents of array
        void printArray(){
            cout << "Elements in the Array are: ";
            for (int i = 0; i < size; ++i){
              cout << *(arr + i) <<" "; // accessing and printing values
           }
            cout<<endl; 
        }

        // method to deallocate memory
        void deleteArray() {
            delete[] arr; // deallocating array memory
        }
};

int main(){
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the size of Array: ";
    cin >> n; 

    ArrayHandler handler; 

    handler.allocArray(n);
    handler.fillArray();
    handler.printArray();
    handler.deleteArray();

    return 0;
}
```
In this program, the `new` operator is used to dynamically allocate memory for an array of a given size when `allocArray()` method is called. The `fillArray()` function then fills in those allocated elements with numbers from 1 to n (where n is the size). After printing the contents of the array, `delete[] arr;` deallocates the dynamically allocated memory for the array.

